D208 Predictive Modeling¶

Performance Assessment 2¶

Caleb Jantsch¶

A1: Research Question¶

 What combination of variables can best be used to predict churn?

A2: Goal of Analysis¶

 The purpose of this analysis is to discover if there is a set of variables that can be used to predict whether or not a customer will churn. This is important to the organization because it can be used to forecast future customer numbers and revenue. It can also lay the ground work for determining the cause of churn among certain customers and allow the organization to prepare strategies for improved customer retention.

B1: Assumptions of Multiple Logistic Regression¶

  1. The dependant variable is binary. This means that the dependent variable can only have two possible outcomes.

  2. The observations used are independent. This means that the data used should not come from repeated measurements of the same individual or have any other relationship.

  3. The independent variables are not highly correlated with one another.

  4. There are no outliers that are so extreme as to overly influence the data.

  5. There is a linear relationship between the explanatory variables and the logit of the dependent variable.

  6. The sample size used is large enough for the number of explanatory variables used in the analysis (Bobbitt, 2020).

B2: Benefits of Using Python¶

 Python was chosen for this analysis due to its simple intuitive syntax and its host of easy to use packages that make linear regression simple to execute.

B3: Justification for Using Logistic Regression to Answer Research Question¶

 For this analysis, we are trying to create a model that will allow us to predict an outcome based on a set of observations. Logistic regression is being used because the outcome we are trying to predict is binary as opposed to linear regression which is used to try and predict a continuous numerical value.

C1: Data Cleaning¶

 The goal of data cleaning in this analysis is to check for null values and treat them, ensure that qualitative variables do not contain any typos that would create extra variables when performing one hot encoding, and to look for and assess outliers amongst the quantitative variables.

Generate Boxplots of Quantitative Variables to Check for Outliers¶

 To assess my quantitative variables for outliers, I generated a boxplot for each variable and then used the length function and value counts method to determine the number of outliers. I chose not to treat any of the outliers except children and the reasoning for each variable can be found below.

In [20]:
sns.boxplot(data=churn, x='population')
Out[20]:
<Axes: xlabel='population'>
In [21]:
print('Number of Outliers:', len(churn.loc[churn['population']>30000, 'population']))

Number of Outliers: 1043

 Roughly ten percent of the data set are outliers. However, the numbers are not completely unrealistic for people living in large cities. The outliers may simply be a result of having a large number of customers in rural towns and cities. The outliers will not be treated.

# impute younger outliers with the median for their age group

In [26]:

Out[26]:
Series([], Name: count, dtype: int64)

 Outliers for the children variable make up around four percent of the data set. Further investigation showed that some of these outliers were quite young for how many children they supposedly had. These values were deemed unrealistic and were imputed with the median number of children for their age group. The other outliers were left untreated since they do not represent an unrealistic number of children for someone over thirty and could be a significant observation for the data.

C4: Data Transformation¶

 The following steps were taken to prepare the data for analysis. First, I changed the values of the dependent variable to be 1 or 0. Then, the strings in the qualitative variables were adjusted to prepare them for one hot encoding. Then, I created dummy variables using the pandas get dummies function with drop first set to true so that one fewer dummy variable was produced than the number of unique values in the original column. This was done to prevent multicollinearity amongst the variables. Having dummy variables for every unique value produces multicollinearity because the value for one dummy in a certain row can be inferred based on the values of the other dummies. Then I calculated the VIF scores for my variables to check for multicollinearity amongst all of the variables and dropped any variables that had high scores.

In [114]:
# change churn variable to contain 1 or 0

D2: Model Reduction Technique¶

 To improve the performance of the model and reduce the number of variables used, I will use backward stepwise elimination to reduce the model. This involves eliminating the least significant variables one by one to improve model performance. The variables are chosen based on their p-value(shown as P>|z| on the summary table). Variables will be dropped until there are no variables left with a p-value greater than 0.05 or the model ceases to see improvements from eliminating variables.

In [124]:
# reduce model using backward stepwise elimination
# remove outage_sec_perweek
formula_v2 = '''churn ~ population + children + age + income + email + contacts + yearly_equip_failure
                + tenure + monthlycharge + item1 + item2 + item3 + item4 + item5 + item6 + item7 + item8
                + area_suburban + area_urban + marital_never_married + marital_separated + marital_widowed + gender_male
                + gender_nonbinary + contract_one_year + contract_two_year + internetservice_fiber_optic + internetservice_none
                + marital_married'''

E1: Comparison of Initial and Reduced Models¶

 In the initial model, I started with thirty independent variables and an AIC score of 4737.36. After gradually eliminating the least significant variables using backward stepwise elimination, the final reduced model contains ten independent variables and has an AIC score of 4703.15. The AIC score indicates how well a model fits the data while penalizing for errors created by additional variables. The lower the score the better the model fits the data. The reduced model has a lower score indicating that it is overall a better model than the initial model.

F1: Discussion of Results¶

Regression Equation and Interpretation of Coefficients¶

The regression equation for the reduced model is as follows:

ln(p/(1-p)) = -6.3799 + 0.0615(contacts) - 0.1078(tenure) + 0.0551(monthlycharge) + 0.1357(marital_separated) + 0.2517(marital_widowed) + 0.2475(gender_male) - 3.1609(contract_one_year) - 3.2614(contract_two_year) - 2.3468(internetservice_fiber_optic) - 0.6202(internetservice_none)

 The intercept and coefficients shown are the log odds of the independent variables. Since log odds can be difficult to interpret, I will mostly discuss them using the odds ratio and change in odds calculated in section E2. The intercept can be used to give the probability that the customer will churn if all the independent variables are zero. The calculation shown in E2 indicates that a customer has a less than one percent chance of churning in this case.

 Variables with an odds ratio of less than one indicate a reduction in the probability of the customer churning. The tenure variable has an odds ratio of 0.8977. This corresponds to a 10.22 percent decrease in the odds that the customer will churn with every unit increase of a customer's tenure, meaning that the longer a customer stays with the company the less likely they are to churn. The one year and two year contract variables have odds ratios of 0.0423 and 0.0383 respectively. This means that one year and two year customers have over a 95 percent reduction in odds of churning over month to month customers when looking at the change in odds. The fiber optic and none internet service variables have odds ratios of 0.0956 and 0.5378 respectively. This translates to fiber customers having a 90 percent decrease in odds and customers without internet having a 46 percent decrease in odds of churning with respect to DSL customers.

 Variables with an odds ratio more than one indicate an increase in the probability of the customer churning. The contacts variable has an odds ratio of 1.0635. This means that for each unit increase of contacts the odds of a customer churning increases by 6.35 percent. This indicates that the more a customer contacts the company the more likely they are to churn. The monthly charge variable has an odds ratio of 1.0567. This means that for each unit increase of monthly charge the odds of the customer churning increase by 5.67 percent, indicating that the likelihood of a customer churning increases the higher their monthly bill is. The marital separated and widowed variables have odds ratios of 1.1454 and 1.2862 respectively. This means that the odds of churning increase 14.5 and 28.6 percent over customers who are single. The gender male variable has and odds ratio of 1.2808. This indicates that males have a 28 percent increase in odds of churning over females.

Statistical and Practical Significance of Model¶

 The p-value for the model (shown as LLR p-value in summary table) is less than 0.05. This means that the regression of the combination of independent variables is statistically significant. In addition, the model does not violate any of the assumptions necessary for performing logistic regression. Therefore, we can conclude that the model is statistically significant.

 In section E2, I calculated the accuracy, sensitivity and specificity of the model. The model has an accuracy of 0.89, meaning that it is able to correctly predict whether or not a customer will churn around eighty nine percent of the time. The sensitivity, which looks at how accurate it can predict a customer will churn, is 0.779. The specificity, which looks at how accurate the model can predict a customer won't churn, is 0.937. This indicates that the model is better at identifying customers who won't churn as opposed to those who will churn. However, I believe that the model is accurate enough to be of practical use to the organization once it has be tested against other data sets to confirm the results.

Limitations of Logistic Regression¶

There are several limitations to logistic regression:

  • The model is sensitive to extreme outliers. Outliers can have an outsized impact on the coefficients of the independent variables and affect model accuracy.

  • The model is prone to overfitting. This means that the model is only useful for the data used to create it and can not be used on other data rendering the model useless.

F2: Course of Action¶

 The model produced is has potential to be useful to the organization but first the model needs to be validated against other data sets to ensure that the model is good. My recommendation is to cross validate the model with other data before putting it to use for business decisions.
